## Layering

Each project layer depends only on layers below it. Never the reverse.

| Layer | Examples here | Depends on |
|---|---|---|
| Presentation | `web.py`, `cli.py`, `report.py` | Orchestration |
| Orchestration | `harness.py`, `session.py` | Engine + Eval |
| Engine | `learner.py`, `tutor.py` | Domain + Protocol |
| Evaluation | `evaluator.py`, `comparator.py`, `detectors.py`, `goldenset.py` | Domain + Protocol |
| Domain | `curriculum.py`, `personas.py`, `protocol.py` | (none) |

Concretely:
- A change to `curriculum.py` may force changes in any layer above, never below.
- The dashboard (`web.py`) must never be imported by the harness — only the
  reverse.
- Tests live in `tests/`, parallel to `src/`, and import only public surfaces
  (no `from slh.web._private import ...`).

## Module responsibility

One reason to change per module. If a module has two unrelated reasons to be
edited, it's two modules waiting to be split.

When extending:
- New eval dimension → `evaluator.py` + `report.py` thresholds + golden gate.
- New persona archetype → `personas.py` only (don't fork policy into another file).
- New tutor version → `tutor.py` subclass; do not duplicate session logic.
- New audience view → one function in `web.py`; share helpers (`_persona_table`,
  `_falls_short_section`, `_nav`); the build script renders it to a static
  file.

## Anti-patterns

- Reaching across a layer (e.g. `web.py` calling `session.run_session`
  directly): route through `harness.py` instead.
- A "utils" module that grows into a junk drawer: split by responsibility once
  it exceeds a single coherent concern.
- Circular imports: usually a signal that a shared type should live in
  `protocol.py`.
